High Level Design (HLD): Ollie
Project Ollie High Level Design
Proactive Human-Agent Collaborative Workspace Application
________________


1. Objective
Ollie establishes an enterprise-grade collaborative workspace application that unifies human engineering teams and proactive AI agents into organized Workstreams. By centralizing task triage, contextual understanding, and background execution, Ollie accelerates software development workflows and eliminates context switching across fragmented engineering and communication tools.


________________


2. Background
Modern software engineering and program management teams experience severe context fragmentation across internal and external toolchains—including Google Chat, Gmail, Buganizer, Jira, Critique, and Google Docs. Knowledge workers spend a substantial portion of their working hours manually triaging incoming notifications, drafting routine communication, tracking cross-system status, and scaffolding code or documentation.


Traditional AI assistants operate as passive, chat-based utilities that require continuous human prompting. They lack awareness of shared team memory, cannot execute asynchronous background maintenance, and do not integrate cleanly into existing role-based access control (RBAC) boundaries. Ollie bridges this gap by introducing proactive AI agents as first-class, authenticated collaborative teammates within persistent workstreams.


________________


3. Overview & System Architecture
Ollie's architecture is structured into decoupled functional tiers: client presentation, multi-channel event ingestion, core domain microservices (Ollie BE), isolated intelligence repositories (Memory Service), proactive agent runtimes (Agency), sandboxed engineering actuation (Cloudtop / Capsules), and relational/vector storage engines (Ollie Spanner and Memory DB).


  
[a]
________________


4. Detailed Subsystem Specifications
4.1 Ingestion Listeners (Push and Pull)
The ingestion layer captures multi-channel events across communication and tracking systems, normalizing disparate payloads into standard task creation requests routed to Task Service:


* WS Events: Processes real-time push webhooks and notifications from Gmail threads and Google Chat spaces.
* 1P Tools: Executes periodic pull polling and captures event updates from Google internal systems (Buganizer tickets, Critique code reviews).
* 3P Tools: Subscribes to webhooks and polling loops for external tracking platforms (Jira, Asana).
4.2 Ollie UI / FE
The web client is built on the Google Wiz UI framework, providing interactive task boards, collaborative activity streams, and conversational agent interfaces..
4.3 Ollie BE (Core Domain Microservices)
The backend application server is cleanly partitioned into four domain microservices:


1. Task Service:
   * Authoritative gateway for task lifecycle CRUD, workstream placement inference, and sub-task tree hierarchies.
   * Manages canonical Task records in Ollie Spanner.
2. Task Fulfilment Service:
   * Central execution dispatcher that translates declarative task intents into runtime actuation.
   * Routes cognitive communication workflows (Sobi Tasks) to the Sojo Actor and technical engineering workflows (Coding tasks) to Jetski on Cloudtop / Capsules.
3. Feed Service:
   * Authoritative timeline manager storing activity cards, interactive widgets, and comment threads in Ollie Spanner (Feeds).
   * Broadcasts real-time updates to web clients.
4. Workstream Service:
   * Tenant authority and RBAC gatekeeper managing workspace metadata and membership lists in Ollie Spanner (Workstreams cylinder).
   * Synchronizes workspace asset bindings (Google Groups, Shared Drives, Buganizer Hotlists, Chat spaces).
4.4 Memory Service & Memory DB
The intelligence service responsible for long-term factual recall, engineering guidelines, and semantic vector indexing:


* Operates against Memory DB (Memory).
* Enforces strict multi-tenant boundaries across four tiers: Private, Workstream, Team, and Global.


For this, we can consider reusing the Memory infra built for Sobi.
4.5 Agency Suite
The proactive AI intelligence and ReAct reasoning framework:


* Sobi Harness: Jetski Prod V2 (go/jetski-prod-v2) actor executing multi-step tool calls against Workspace MCP servers (Drive, Docs, Gmail, Chat, Buganizer, Critique), Headless agents, VMs etc.
* Memory Reflection Hook: Asynchronous background daemon that distills completed task trajectories into permanent memory nodes.
* Ollie System Instructions: Curated prompt instructions, persona definitions, and Top-and-Bottom Human-in-the-Loop (HITL) governance rules.
* Memory Dream Cron: Periodic background scheduler that drives vector clustering consolidation, unassigned task discovery, and morning digest synthesis.
* Ollie Hooks (Posting to Feed, Updating tasks): Specialized callback extensions enabling running agents and Dream Cron sweeps to asynchronously update canonical task states in Task Service and publish notification cards to Feed Service.
4.6 Cloudtop / Capsules (Sandboxed Engineering Actuation)
The hermetic execution environment for software engineering tasks:


* Jetski Harness: Orchestrates ephemeral container capsules pre-loaded with internal Google3 development toolchains (fig, hg, jj, blaze, build_cleaner, tricorder).
* CLI tools: Actuation utilities executing shell commands.


________________


5. Data & Storage Architecture
Ollie utilizes two physically isolated Google Cloud Spanner database:


1. Ollie Spanner (OllieDB):
   * Workstreams & WorkstreamMemberships: Root workspace tenants and relationally interleaved RBAC membership records.
   * Tasks: Canonical task entities interleaved under Workstreams, featuring recursive parent_task_id hierarchies, multi-source provenance arrays (original_sources), and ScaNN vector indexes for semantic duplicate detection.
   * Feeds & FeedComments: Chronologically ordered activity cards and discussion threads interleaved under Workstreams.
   * ListenerConfigs: Source monitoring and webhook configuration records.
2. Memory DB:
   * MemoryStores: Root hierarchical memory scopes.


________________


6. Cross-Cutting Concerns
6.1 Security & Dual Identity Execution
Ollie enforces strict execution identity separation:


* Personal Tasks: Private tasks (private scope) execute exclusively under the individual user's Gaia session token. Neither Workstream Agents nor other teammates can access private tasks or personal memory stores.
* Workstream Tasks: Team tasks (workstream_visible or shared_restricted scope). When an agent service account delegates an action, the gatekeeper resolves and verifies the initiating human's RBAC permissions.
6.2 Sandboxed Execution & Credential Propagation
All technical code modifications execute inside user owned Cloudtop / Capsules. go/jetski-sidecars will be used to fetch the tasks assigned to the user's Jetski agent and will be executed and posted back to the task service / feed service.
6.3 Top-and-Bottom HITL Governance
To prevent runaway automation and ensure human oversight, workflows enforce a two-stage governance model:


1. Top Refinement: High-level ambiguous goals require explicit user scoping confirmation before automated execution begins.
2. Bottom Sign-off: Upon task completion, compiled code diffs, PRDs, and outbound communication drafts must be reviewed and approved by human teammates in Feed Service before final dispatch.




Written with help of Jetski


Ollie Services: Technical & Architectural Design …
Ollie Services: Technical & Architectural Design Specification
NOTE: Not reviewed by human author yet, generated by Jetski based on the context.
________________


1. Overview & Service Decomposition
The Ollie platform (https://workspace.google.com/ollie) is structured into eight authoritative microservices and execution harnesses. Each service governs a well-defined domain, communicating over standardized Protobuf gRPC interfaces (google.workspace.ollie.v1):


1. Task Service: Authoritative state gateway for canonical task CRUD, sub-task hierarchies, and automated workstream triage.
2. Task Fulfilment Service: Execution routing orchestrator decoupling declarative task intents from runtime actuation.
3. Feed Service: Collaborative activity timeline store and WebSocket/SSE broadcast engine.
4. Workstream Service: Workspace tenant authority, RBAC gatekeeper, and external asset provisioning engine.
5. Memory Service: Tiered intelligence repository for factual recall, engineering guidelines, and semantic vector retrieval.
6. Sobi Harness: Cognitive LLM agent runtime actor for reasoning, Workspace MCP tool execution, and HITL governance.
7. Jetski Harness: Hermetic, sandboxed Cloudtop/Capsules actuator for technical software engineering workflows.
8. Memory Dream Cron: Automated background maintenance daemon for vector clustering, offline triage, and digests.


________________


2. Detailed Service Specifications
2.1 Task Service
2.1.1 Authoritative Responsibilities & Operational Scope
* Canonical State Authority: Manages all CRUD operations against the Tasks table in Ollie Spanner. Enforces strict deterministic state transitions: $$\text{UNTRIAGED} \rightarrow \text{TRIAGED} \rightarrow \text{IN_PROGRESS} \rightarrow \text{PENDING_REVIEW} \rightarrow \text{COMPLETED} \text{ (or } \text{CANCELLED)}$$
* Ingestion Convergence Sink: Serves as the single authoritative entrypoint for all normalized events arriving from Ingestion Listeners (WS Events from Gmail/Chat, Buganizer pollers, Critique adapters, Jira hooks).
* Identity & Access Bounding: Enforces dual-identity execution rules. Private tasks are strictly bound to the creator's Gaia ID. Assigned or team tasks are bound to the Workstream Service Account or the assigned user's Gaia ID, verified against Workstream Service RBAC policies.
2.1.2 Primary RPC Interfaces & Method Contracts
syntax = "proto3";
package google.workspace.ollie.v1;


import "google/protobuf/empty.proto";
import "google/protobuf/field_mask.proto";
import "google/protobuf/timestamp.proto";


service TaskService {
  // Canonical CRUD & State Management
  rpc CreateTask(CreateTaskRequest) returns (Task);
  rpc GetTask(GetTaskRequest) returns (Task);
  rpc ListTasks(ListTasksRequest) returns (ListTasksResponse);
  rpc UpdateTask(UpdateTaskRequest) returns (Task);
  rpc DeleteTask(DeleteTaskRequest) returns (google.protobuf.Empty);


  // Batch Ingestion & Triage Routing
  rpc IngestExternalEvents(IngestExternalEventsRequest) returns (IngestExternalEventsResponse);
  rpc TriageTask(TriageTaskRequest) returns (TriageTaskResponse);
  rpc MergeDuplicateTasks(MergeDuplicateTasksRequest) returns (Task);


  // Sub-task Tree Operations
  rpc CreateSubTask(CreateSubTaskRequest) returns (Task);
  rpc GetTaskTree(GetTaskTreeRequest) returns (TaskTreeResponse);
}


enum TaskStatus {
  TASK_STATUS_UNSPECIFIED = 0;
  TASK_STATUS_UNTRIAGED = 1;
  TASK_STATUS_TRIAGED = 2;
  TASK_STATUS_IN_PROGRESS = 3;
  TASK_STATUS_PENDING_REVIEW = 4;
  TASK_STATUS_COMPLETED = 5;
  TASK_STATUS_CANCELLED = 6;
}


